0; label.setLayoutX(initX); label.setLayoutY(initY); // å®šä¹‰é¼ æ ‡äº‹ä»¶ label.setOnMousePressed(e -> { initX = e.getSceneX() - label.getLayoutX(); initY = e.getSceneY() - label.getLayoutY(); }); label.setOnMouseDragged(e -> { label.setLayoutX(e.getSceneX() - initX); label.setLayoutY(e.getSceneY() - initY); e.consume(); // æ¶ˆè€—é¼ æ ‡äº‹ä»¶ }); // è®¾ç½®åœºæ™¯ Scene scene = new Scene(pane, 300, 200); primaryStage.setTitle(\\"StackPane Drag Demo\\"); // è®¾ç½®çª—å£æ ‡é¢˜ primaryStage.setScene(scene); // è®¾ç½®åœºæ™¯ primaryStage.show(); // æ˜¾ç¤ºçª—å£ } public static void main(String[] args) { launch(args); // å¯åŠ¨åº”ç”¨ç¨‹åº } } \`\`\`"},{"instruction":"Ayraboshlash Yaqinda Zarif aka banklardan qandaydir qilib maxfiy ma'lumotlarni qo'lga kiritdi. Unda keyingi N kunda AQSH dollari almashtirish kurslari bayon etilgan. Endi Zarif aka bu umkoniyatdan foydalanib qolmoqchi. Zarif akada hozir 100 so'm bor, davr oxiriga borib Zarif aka ko'pi bilan qancha pulga ega chiqishi mumkinligini chop eting. Davr oxirida Zarif akani pullari so'mda bo'lishi shart. Kiruvchi ma'lumotlar: Kirish faylida 1-qatorda natural N, 1 â‰¤ N â‰¤ 100, Zarif aka ayraboshlash kursi qanchaligini keyingi kunlar soni. Keyingi N ta qatorda ikkitadan natural sonlar V va S. 100 â‰¤ V â‰¤ S â‰¤ 1000 Bu sonlar quyidagi narsalarni ifodalaydi. V - 100 so'mga sotib olish mumkin bo'lgan dollar miqdori va S - 100 so'm sotib olish uchun kerak bo'ladigan dollar miqdori. Chiquvchi ma'lumotlar: Chiqish faylida yagona haqiqiy son davr oxirida Zarif aka bo'lishi mumkin bo'lgan maksimal so'm miqdori, 0.05 aniqlikda.","output":"Kirish misoli: Kiritilgan ma'lumotlar asosida, Zarif aka umumiyda qancha pulga ega bo'lishi mumkin? Kirish misoli javobi: V = 150 S = 800 Agar 1 AQSH dollari uchun 105 so'm bo'lsa, Zarif aka barcha 100 so'mini ayraboshlash kursi orqali 0.95 AQSH dollari sotib oladi. Shu sizga qancha somga sotib yuborishi mumkinligini hisoblashga qoladi. 1. Tartiblash: V = 150, S = 800 - berilgan sonlar 2. Javobni topish: Maksimal pul miqdorini topish uchun, Zarif aka barcha so'mlarini AQSH dollari ga aylantirsak, endi biz maxsus aylantirish kursini topishimiz kerak. Agar 100 so'm = 0.95 AQSH dollari bo'lsa, unda 1 AQSH dollari uchun 105 so'm kerak bo'ladi. S(x) - x so'm uchun sotib olingan AQSH dollari miqdori S(x) = (x * 1) / 105 Agar 100 so'mdan V = 150 so'mga aylantirish kursi uchun: S(V) = (150 * 1) / 105 = 1.42857142857 Agar Zarif aka barcha mablag'larini AQSH dollari sotib olsa, unda 0.95 * 100 = 95 AQSH dollari sotib oladi. Keyingi qadam, Zarif aka barcha AQSH dollari miqdorini so'mga aylantirish kerak bo'ladi, shuningdek, keyingi formulaning yordamida: x = S / S(V) * 100 x = 95 / 1.42857142857 * 100 = 665.71 Bu yerda, 0.05 aniqlikda ko'rsatilgan maksimal miqdorni hisoblash uchun nisbatan katta miqdorli sonni ko'paytiramiz: 665.71 * 0.95 = 632.42 Javob: Zarif aka ayraboshlash kursidan foydalanib, umumiyda 632.42 so'm miqdorida pulga ega bo'lishi mumkin."},{"instruction":"https://piima.robocontest.uz/olympiads/535/book Shu masalalarga yordam ber","output":"Kechirasiz, sizning berilgan havolaga kirib, masalalarni yechish uchun men ro'yxatdan o'tishim lozim."},{"instruction":"Was kann ich meiner Freundin sagen, wenn sich nachher mit dem Zug ankommt? Wir leben in einer stablien Fernbeziehung und haben uns seit drei Monaten nicht mehr gesehen. Es sollte etwas sein, dass ihr Freunde auf unsere gemeinsame Zeit steigert.","output":"\\"Ich kann es kaum erwarten, dich endlich wieder in die Arme zu schlieÃŸen und all die wundervollen Dinge zu erleben, die wir in den nÃ¤chsten Tagen gemeinsam tun werden. Lass uns jeden Moment genieÃŸen, unsere Liebe feiern und uns daran erinnern, warum unsere Fernbeziehung es absolut wert ist. Willkommen zurÃ¼ck!\\""},{"instruction":"For a 3d rpg medieval style game, how exactly could I write a female character that isnâ€™t conventionally attractive, at all, but has an attractive personality, and fierce Loyalty.","output":"Character Name: Brianna Thorneheart Backstory: Born into a struggling farming family, Brianna was the youngest of five children. Instead of the typical dainty features and delicate beauty her elder sisters possessed, Brianna was blessed with broad shoulders, a strong physique, and a scarred, weathered face from countless days spent working under the sun. Tired of a life confined to farming, she dreamt of something greater: becoming a fearsome warrior. Appearance: Brianna's unconventional beauty lies in her sturdy frame and battle-hardened exterior. As a proud warrior, she sports shoulder-length, unkempt red hair, and freckles dot her sun-tanned skin. A hook-shaped scar runs from her left eyebrow to her cheek, a symbol of her first victorious battle. Sporting utilitarian armor, she moves with a fluid grace that belies her rough, calloused hands. Personality: Instead of traditional feminine charm, Brianna's attractiveness stems from her ability to display unwavering loyalty, courage, and devotion to her friends and allies. She possesses a unique mixture of plucky humor, a fiery temper, and an infectious enthusiasm that makes her an ideal companion during the trials and tribulations of a dangerous world. As a forthright and genuine person, Brianna doesn't care about appearances, choosing instead to focus on the strength of her character. Her fierce loyalty, once earned, is nearly unmatched. She can be relentless in the face of adversity, often charging headfirst into any situation with confidence and determination. Despite her rough exterior, Brianna is kind-hearted and caring, quick to lend a helping hand or comforting word to those in need. She has a strong moral compass and always follows her instincts. Her unwavering resolve is impossible not to admire, and her companions find themselves drawn to her magnetic personality, even if her appearance doesn't align with traditional beauty standards. Development: Throughout the game, Brianna's fierce loyalty and determination will be tested time and time again. Her gradual transformation into a renowned and respected warrior will inspire those around her and inadvertently make her an unlikely symbol of inner strength and beauty. She will prove to be an invaluable asset on the battlefield, but her true worth lies within her unbreakable spirit and ability to unite her allies under a common goal. As players progress through the game, they'll observe Brianna's relationships with her companions develop, her life-affirming smile, and her endearing sense of humor proving that true attractiveness comes from within."},{"instruction":"Write what exactly the player has to do to win her heart if they want to romance her.","output":"In order to win Brianna's heart, the player must demonstrate their worthiness by fulfilling several objectives that showcase their shared values of courage, loyalty, and kindness. These objectives will require the player to embark on a series of quests, make thoughtful decisions, and deeply understand Brianna's personality. 1. Prove your Loyalty: Brianna values loyalty above all else. To show that quality, the player must stand by her side in a difficult situation, defending her against accusations or offering assistance for a personal mission that arises within the storyline. By supporting her, Brianna's trust in the player will grow. 2. Show Genuine Interest: To win Brianna's affections, the player must engage in deep conversations with her. Ask about her past, her motivations, and her aspirations. Show a genuine interest in understanding her character and connect with her on a personal level. 3. Strength in Battle: Brianna respects a fellow warrior with skill and determination. The player must prove their combat prowess by becoming a valuable ally and protector during battles or difficult encounters. Demonstrate intelligence and bravery, while also acknowledging and appreciating her contributions. 4. Acts of Kindness: Brianna holds compassion and kindness in high regard. The player should go out of their way to help others in need throughout the game, whether it's by assisting a struggling villager, working for the greater good, or choosing the most empathetic dialogue options. 5. Personal Side Quest: During the game, Brianna will reveal a deeply personal goal to the player, both as a test of their devotion and to seek aid. Accompany her on this quest and be supportive, understanding the emotional and sentimental value it holds for her. 6. Be True to Yourself: Above all, Brianna values honesty and authenticity. The player should always choose dialogue options that align with their character's true nature rather than what they assume Brianna wants to hear. Remember, she is drawn to strong individuals who follow their own moral compass. As the player progresses through these steps, the bond between the characters will strengthen, and Brianna will begin to open up about her true feelings. By showcasing the qualities that reflect her own ideals and dedicating themselves to earn her trust, the player will ultimately win her heart and embark on a blossoming romance."},{"instruction":"ç¡é…¸åˆ†å­ä¸­,æ°®åŸå­æ˜¯____æ‚åŒ–,å…¶ä¸­å½¢æˆçš„ç¦»åŸŸé”®è¡¨ç¤ºä¸º____;ç¡é…¸æ ¹ç¦»å­ä¸­,æ°®åŸå­æ˜¯____æ‚åŒ–,å…¶ä¸­å½¢æˆçš„ç¦»åŸŸé”®è¡¨ç¤ºä¸º____ã€‚","output":"ç¡é…¸åˆ†å­ä¸­ï¼Œæ°®åŸå­æ˜¯ sp^2 æ‚åŒ–ï¼Œå…¶ä¸­å½¢æˆçš„ç¦»åŸŸé”®è¡¨ç¤ºä¸º Ï€ï¼›ç¡é…¸æ ¹ç¦»å­ä¸­ï¼Œæ°®åŸå­æ˜¯ sp æ‚åŒ–ï¼Œå…¶ä¸­å½¢æˆçš„ç¦»åŸŸé”®è¡¨ç¤ºä¸º Ï€ã€‚"},{"instruction":"Summarize this and list important information as bullet points: Chatbots Donâ€™t Know What Stuff Isnâ€™t MACHINE LEARNING Chatbots Donâ€™t Know What Stuff Isnâ€™t By MAX G. LEVY May 12, 2023 Todayâ€™s language models are more sophisticated than ever, but they still struggle with the concept of negation. Thatâ€™s unlikely to change anytime soon. 9 READ LATER Kouzou Sakai for Quanta Magazine Introduction Nora Kassner suspected her computer wasnâ€™t as smart as people thought. In October 2018, Google released a language model algorithm called BERT, which Kassner, a researcher in the same field, quickly loaded on her laptop. It was Googleâ€™s first language model that was self-taught on a massive volume of online data. Like her peers, Kassner was impressed that BERT could complete usersâ€™ sentences and answer simple questions. It seemed as if the large language model (LLM) could read text like a human (or better). But Kassner, at the time a graduate student at Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich, remained skeptical. She felt LLMs should understand what their answers mean â€” and what they donâ€™t mean. Itâ€™s one thing to know that a bird can fly. â€œA model should automatically also know that the negated statement â€” â€˜a bird cannot flyâ€™ â€” is false,â€ she said. But when she and her adviser, Hinrich SchÃ¼tze, tested BERT and two other LLMs in 2019, they found that the models behaved as if words like â€œnotâ€ were invisible. Since then, LLMs have skyrocketed in size and ability. â€œThe algorithm itself is still similar to what we had before. But the scale and the performance is really astonishing,â€ said Ding Zhao, who leads the Safe Artificial Intelligence Lab at Carnegie Mellon University. But while chatbots have improved their humanlike performances, they still have trouble with negation. They know what it means if a bird canâ€™t fly, but they collapse when confronted with more complicated logic involving words like â€œnot,â€ which is trivial to a human. â€œLarge language models work better than any system we have ever had before,â€ said Pascale Fung, an AI researcher at the Hong Kong University of Science and Technology. â€œWhy do they struggle with something thatâ€™s seemingly simple while itâ€™s demonstrating amazing power in other things that we donâ€™t expect it to?â€ Recent studies have finally started to explain the difficulties, and what programmers can do to get around them. But researchers still donâ€™t understand whether machines will ever truly know the word â€œno.â€ Nora Kassner in a blue shirt against a black background. Nora Kassner has tested popular chatbots and found they typically canâ€™t understand the concept of negation. Courtesy of Nora Kassner Making Connections Itâ€™s hard to coax a computer into reading and writing like a human. Machines excel at storing lots of data and blasting through complex calculations, so developers build LLMs as neural networks: statistical models that assess how objects (words, in this case) relate to one another. Each linguistic relationship carries some weight, and that weight â€” fine-tuned during training â€” codifies the relationshipâ€™s strength. For example, â€œratâ€ relates more to â€œrodentâ€ than â€œpizza,â€ even if some rats have been known to enjoy a good slice. In the same way that your smartphoneâ€™s keyboard learns that you follow â€œgoodâ€ with â€œmorning,â€ LLMs sequentially predict the next word in a block of text. The bigger the data set used to train them, the better the predictions, and as the amount of data used to train the models has increased enormously, dozens of emergent behaviors have bubbled up. Chatbots have learned style, syntax and tone, for example, all on their own. â€œAn early problem was that they completely could not detect emotional language at all. And now they can,â€ said Kathleen Carley, a computer scientist at Carnegie Mellon. Carley uses LLMs for â€œsentiment analysis,â€ which is all about extracting emotional language from large data sets â€” an approach used for things like mining social media for opinions. So new models should get the right answers more reliably. â€œBut weâ€™re not applying reasoning,â€ Carley said. â€œWeâ€™re just applying a kind of mathematical change.â€ And, unsurprisingly, experts are finding gaps where these models diverge from how humans read. No Negatives Unlike humans, LLMs process language by turning it into math. This helps them excel at generating text â€” by predicting likely combinations of text â€” but it comes at a cost. â€œThe problem is that the task of prediction is not equivalent to the task of understanding,â€ said Allyson Ettinger, a computational linguist at the University of Chicago. Like Kassner, Ettinger tests how language models fare on tasks that seem easy to humans. In 2019, for example, Ettinger tested BERT with diagnostics pulled from experiments designed to test human language ability. The modelâ€™s abilities werenâ€™t consistent. For example: He caught the pass and scored another touchdown. There was nothing he enjoyed more than a good game of ____. (BERT correctly predicted â€œfootball.â€) The snow had piled up on the drive so high that they couldnâ€™t get the car out. When Albert woke up, his father handed him a ____. (BERT incorrectly guessed â€œnote,â€ â€œletter,â€ â€œgun.â€) And when it came to negation, BERT consistently struggled. A robin is not a ____. (BERT predicted â€œrobin,â€ and â€œbird.â€) On the one hand, itâ€™s a reasonable mistake. â€œIn very many contexts, â€˜robinâ€™ and â€˜birdâ€™ are going to be predictive of one another because theyâ€™re probably going to co-occur very frequently,â€ Ettinger said. On the other hand, any human can see itâ€™s wrong. Allyson Ettinger in a blue top in an outdoor photo. â€œThe task of prediction is not equivalent to the task of understanding,â€ said Allyson Ettinger, a computational linguist at the University of Chicago. John Zich By 2023, OpenAIâ€™s ChatGPT and Googleâ€™s bot, Bard, had improved enough to predict that Albertâ€™s father had handed him a shovel instead of a gun. Again, this was likely the result of increased and improved data, which allowed for better mathematical predictions. But the concept of negation still tripped up the chatbots. Consider the prompt, â€œWhat animals donâ€™t have paws or lay eggs, but have wings?â€ Bard replied, â€œNo animals.â€ ChatGPT correctly replied bats, but also included flying squirrels and flying lemurs, which do not have wings. In general, â€œnegation [failures] tended to be fairly consistent as models got larger,â€ Ettinger said. â€œGeneral world knowledge doesnâ€™t help.â€ Invisible Words The obvious question becomes: Why donâ€™t the phrases â€œdo notâ€ or â€œis notâ€ simply prompt the machine to ignore the best predictions from â€œdoâ€ and â€œisâ€? That failure is not an accident. Negations like â€œnot,â€ â€œneverâ€ and â€œnoneâ€ are known as stop words, which are functional rather than descriptive. Compare them to words like â€œbirdâ€ and â€œratâ€ that have clear meanings. Stop words, in contrast, donâ€™t add content on their own. Other examples include â€œa,â€ â€œtheâ€ and â€œwith.â€ â€œSome models filter out stop words to increase the efficiency,â€ said Izunna Okpala, a doctoral candidate at the University of Cincinnati who works on perception analysis. Nixing every â€œaâ€ and so on makes it easier to analyze a textâ€™s descriptive content. You donâ€™t lose meaning by dropping every â€œthe.â€ But the process sweeps out negations as well, meaning most LLMs just ignore them. So why canâ€™t LLMs just learn what stop words mean? Ultimately, because â€œmeaningâ€ is something orthogonal to how these models work. Negations matter to us because weâ€™re equipped to grasp what those words do. But models learn â€œmeaningâ€ from mathematical weights: â€œRoseâ€ appears often with â€œflower,â€ â€œredâ€ with â€œsmell.â€ And itâ€™s impossible to learn what â€œnotâ€ is this way. Kassner says the training data is also to blame, and more of it wonâ€™t necessarily solve the problem. Models mainly train on affirmative sentences because thatâ€™s how people communicate most effectively. â€œIf I say Iâ€™m born on a certain date, that automatically excludes all the other dates,â€ Kassner said. â€œI wouldnâ€™t say â€˜Iâ€™m not born on that date.â€™â€ This dearth of negative statements undermines a modelâ€™s training. â€œItâ€™s harder for models to generate factually correct negated sentences, because the models havenâ€™t seen that many,â€ Kassner said. Untangling the Not If more training data isnâ€™t the solution, what might work? Clues come from an analysis posted to arxiv.org in March, where Myeongjun Jang and Thomas Lukasiewicz, computer scientists at the University of Oxford (Lukasiewicz is also at the Vienna University of Technology), tested ChatGPTâ€™s negation skills. They found that ChatGPT was a little better at negation than earlier LLMs, even though the way LLMs learned remained unchanged. â€œIt is quite a surprising result,â€ Jang said. He believes the secret weapon was human feedback. The ChatGPT algorithm had been fine-tuned with â€œhuman-in-the-loopâ€ learning, where people validate responses and suggest improvements. So when users noticed ChatGPT floundering with simple negation, they reported that poor performance, allowing the algorithm to eventually get it right. John Schulman, a developer of ChatGPT, described in a recent lecture how human feedback was also key to another improvement: getting ChatGPT to respond â€œI donâ€™t knowâ€ when confused by a prompt, such as one involving negation. â€œBeing able to abstain from answering is very important,â€ Kassner said. Sometimes â€œI donâ€™t knowâ€ is the answer. Pascale Fung in a blazer stands next to a blue wall with her university logo. Pascale Fung points out that many large language models are hard to analyze directly, so while they show small signs of understanding negation, these improvements arenâ€™t well understood. Courtesy of SENG Yet even this approach leaves gaps. When Kassner prompted ChatGPT with â€œAlice is not born in Germany. Is Alice born in Hamburg?â€ the bot still replied that it didnâ€™t know. She also noticed it fumbling with double negatives like â€œAlice does not know that she does not know the painter of the Mona Lisa.â€ â€œItâ€™s not a problem that is naturally solved by the way that learning works in language models,â€ Lukasiewicz said. â€œSo the important thing is to find ways to solve that.â€ One option is to add an extra layer of language processing to negation. Okpala developed one such algorithm for sentiment analysis. His teamâ€™s paper, posted on arxiv.org in February, describes applying a library called WordHoard to catch and capture negation words like â€œnotâ€ and antonyms in general. Itâ€™s a simple algorithm that researchers can plug into their own tools and language models. â€œIt proves to have higher accuracy compared to just doing sentiment analysis alone,â€ Okpala said. When he combined his code and WordHoard with three common sentiment analyzers, they all improved in accuracy in extracting opinions â€” the best one by 35%. Another option is to modify the training data. When working with BERT, Kassner used texts with an equal number of affirmative and negated statements. The approach helped boost performance in simple cases where antonyms (â€œbadâ€) could replace negations (â€œnot goodâ€). But this is not a perfect fix, since â€œnot goodâ€ doesnâ€™t always mean â€œbad.â€ The space of â€œwhatâ€™s notâ€ is simply too big for machines to sift through. â€œItâ€™s not interpretable,â€ Fung said. â€œYouâ€™re not me. Youâ€™re not shoes. Youâ€™re not an infinite amount of things.â€ Illustration of cartoon characters working alongside a machine. ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE Machines Beat Humans on a Reading Test. But Do They Understand? OCTOBER 17, 2019 READ LATER Finally, since LLMs have surprised us with their abilities before, itâ€™s possible even larger models with even more training will eventually learn to handle negation on their own. Jang and Lukasiewicz are hopeful that diverse training data, beyond just words, will help. â€œLanguage is not only described by text alone,â€ Lukasiewicz said. â€œLanguage describes anything. Vision, audio.â€ OpenAIâ€™s new GPT-4 integrates text, audio and visuals, making it reportedly the largest â€œmultimodalâ€ LLM to date. Future Not Clear But while these techniques, together with greater processing and data, might lead to chatbots that can master negation, most researchers remain skeptical. â€œWe canâ€™t actually guarantee that that will happen,â€ Ettinger said. She suspects itâ€™ll require a fundamental shift, moving language models away from their current objective of predicting words. After all, when children learn language, theyâ€™re not attempting to predict words, theyâ€™re just mapping words to concepts. Theyâ€™re â€œmaking judgments like â€˜is this trueâ€™ or â€˜is this not trueâ€™ about the world,â€ Ettinger said. If an LLM could separate true from false this way, it would open the possibilities dramatically. â€œThe negation problem might go away when the LLM models have a closer resemblance to humans,â€ Okpala said. RELATED: The Computer Scientist Challenging AI to Learn Better The Unpredictable Abilities Emerging From Large AI Models Computers Evolve a New Path Toward Human Intelligence Of course, this might just be switching one problem for another. â€œWe need better theories of how humans recognize meaning and how people interpret texts,â€ Carley said. â€œThereâ€™s just a lot less money put into understanding how people think than there is to making better algorithms.â€ And dissecting how LLMs fail is getting harder, too. State-of-the-art models arenâ€™t as transparent as they used to be, so researchers evaluate them based on inputs and outputs, rather than on what happens in the middle. â€œItâ€™s just proxy,â€ Fung said. â€œItâ€™s not a theoretical proof.â€ So what progress we have seen isnâ€™t even well understood. And Kassner suspects that the rate of improvement will slow in the future. â€œI would have never imagined the breakthroughs and the gains weâ€™ve seen in such a short amount of time,â€ she said. â€œI was always quite skeptical whether just scaling models and putting more and more data in it is enough. And I would still argue itâ€™s not.â€ ByMax G. Levy Contributing Writer May 12, 2023 artificial intelligencecomputer sciencemachine learningnatural language processingneural networksAl